ce:section.ce:para:
Two brands of pork and chicken sausage, pork and chicken ham, bacon and smoked pork were used for detecting TRY using the MIPs based on CN-embedded COFs. TRY was found in all 12 meat samples (Table 1
                        ), with the greatest concentration in pork sausage at 182.84 μg kg−1. To test the novel sensor for analyzing a real sample, pork sausage was used for the recovery experiment at an extra 25, 50, 100 μg kg−1 of the target standard, and equal and twice the analog standards were added (Table 2
                        ). The recovery in these three parallel measurements ranged from 91.42% to 119.80%, suggesting good levels of practicality and reproducibility in a real sample determination. We have summarized literature on TRY determination of various foods by different methods for detection purposes in terms of detection limit, linear range, reproducibility, stability and recovery. The date has been listed in Table S1. Compared to different methods used for TRY detection, the developed method in the study exhibited better sensitivity, reproducibility and stability.
